Disable 'getenv' test, as it counts the number of function calls to 'getenv',
and compares it to an expected number, disregarding potential 'getenv' calls from the
system.
As this can cause spurious failures, avoid running the test entirely.

Author: Jan Reuter (j.reuter@fz-juelich.de)

diff --color -Naur hpctoolkit-2026.0.1.orig/tests/hpcrun/cpu/meson.build hpctoolkit-2026.0.1/tests/hpcrun/cpu/meson.build
--- hpctoolkit-2026.0.1.orig/tests/hpcrun/cpu/meson.build	2026-05-05 02:38:23.000000000 +0200
+++ hpctoolkit-2026.0.1/tests/hpcrun/cpu/meson.build	2026-05-18 12:17:31.107471095 +0200
@@ -9,7 +9,10 @@
 )
 
 subdir('dtv')
-subdir('getenv')
+# getenv test is sensetive to host environment and can fail because system calls
+# are wrapped as well, with the test counting the number of calls to 'getenv'.
+# Hence, disable the test to avoid spurious failures due to a broken test.
+# subdir('getenv')
 subdir('itimer')
 subdir('papi')
 subdir('perf')
